* We will use stack STL here. 
* Firstly, if the character is a ( , we will push the index value of ( in the stack.
* If the char is ) and stack is not empty, we have the index i (from the traversal itself) and we can pop one ( from the stack..before popping we can take its index value from the stack-top in another variable, say x.
* So, by doing so, we are getting pairs of ( and ), thus making a valid parenthesis (MAYBE not the longest one). Now, for the indices of ( and ) pairs already encountered, make (s[i]='.').
* At the end of traversal, we will be having string s as combinations of ( , ) and '.' 

* e.g., if the string is ")(()()())))", the resulting string becomes - ")........))"
* Now, traverse the string just once to find the longest number of consecutive '.' and that's our answer ! 
* The code - 
* ```     
*     class Solution {
         public:  
    int longestValidParentheses(string s) {
        int i = 0;
        int x;
        int l = 0;
        stack<int> st;
        int res = 0;

        while (s[i] != '\0')
        {
            if (s[i] == '(')
            {
                st.push(i);
                s[i] = '(';
            }
            else
            {
                if (!(st.empty()))
                {
                    x = st.top();
                    st.pop();
                    s[x] = '.';
                    s[i] = '.';
                }
            }
            i++;
        }
        int a = 0;
        for (i = 0; s[i] != '\0'; i++)
        {
            if (s[i] != '.')
            {
                res = max(a, res);
                a = 0;
            }
            else
            {
                a++;
            }
        }
        return max(res,a);
    }
};```

