# **Approach 1** **(TLE)**

```cpp
bool isPalindrome(int i, int j, string &s)
{
    while(i<j)
    {
        if(s[i]!=s[j]) return false;
        i++; j--;
    }
    return true;
}
int solve(vector<vector<int>> &dp, int i, int j, string &s)
{
    if(i>=j) return 0;
    if(dp[i][j]!= -1) return dp[i][j];
    if( isPalindrome(i, j, s) ) return 0;
    int ans = INT_MAX;
    for(int k=i;k<j;k++)
        ans = min(ans, solve(dp, i, k, s) + solve(dp, k+1, j, s) + 1);

    return dp[i][j] = ans;
}
int minCut(string s)
{
    int n = s.size();
    vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(n, -1));
    return solve(dp, 0, n-1, s);
}
```

Approach 1 is based on Matrix Chain Multiplication method(if you don't know Matrix Chain Multiplication please check that), we are considering answer for each intermediate index of string and recursively solving for those substring```s(i, k)``` and ```s(k+1, j)``` and selecting the best answer.

Here multiple overlapping problems will occur so we are memoizing the answer calculated and reusing when it appears next time.
**Time Complexity** - O(n<sup>3</sup>)
**Space Complexity** - O(n<sup>2</sup>)
Time Complexity of above approach is O(n<sup>3</sup>) Because there are O(n<sup>2</sup>) sub problems(all possible partion of string) and for each subproblem we are checking whether it is palindrome or not in O(n) time. 

# **Approach 2 (Accepted)**
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
bool isPalindrome(vector<vector<int>> &pdp, int i, int j, string &s)
{
    if(i>j) return 1;
    if(i==j) return pdp[i][j] = 1;
    if(pdp[i][j] != -1) return pdp[i][j];
    if(s[i] != s[j]) return pdp[i][j] = 0;
    pdp[i][j] =  isPalindrome(pdp, i+1, j-1, s) ;
    return pdp[i][j];
}
int solve(vector<vector<int>> &dp, int i, int j, string &s, vector<vector<int>> &pdp)
{
    if(i>=j) return 0;
    if(dp[i][j]!= -1) return dp[i][j];
    if( pdp[i][j] == 1 ) return dp[i][j] = 0;
    int ans = INT_MAX;
    for(int k=i;k<j;k++)
        if(pdp[i][k])
             ans = min(ans, solve(dp, i, k, s, pdp) + solve(dp, k+1, j, s, pdp) + 1);

    return dp[i][j] = ans;
}
int minCut(string s) 
{
    int n = s.size();
    vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(n, -1));
    vector<vector<int>> pdp(n, vector<int>(n, -1));
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        for(int j=i;j<n;j++)
            isPalindrome(pdp, i, j, s);
    return solve(dp, 0, n-1, s, pdp);
}
};
```

Approach 2 is just optimisation in checking is palindrome. Here we are pre-calculating whether string(i, j) is palindrome or not.
```pdp[i][j]``` indicates that wheter ```s(i, j)``` is palindrome or not using dynamic programming.

**Time Complexity** - O(n<sup>2</sup>)
**Space Complexity** - O(n<sup>2</sup>)
Time Complexity of above approach is O(n<sup>2</sup>) only because there are O(n<sup>2</sup>) sub problems(all possible partion of string) and for each subproblem we are checking whether it is palindrome or not in O(1).
And to check whether a substring is palindrome or not we are pre computing in O(n<sup>2</sup>). So, overall time complexity will be O(n<sup>2</sup> + n<sup>2</sup> ) = O(n<sup>2</sup>) only.


# **Approach 3 (Accepted and Best)**
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int minCut(string s) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<int> cut(n+1, 0);  // number of cuts for the first k characters
        for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) cut[i] = i-1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; i-j >= 0 && i+j < n && s[i-j]==s[i+j] ; j++) // odd length palindrome
                cut[i+j+1] = min(cut[i+j+1],1+cut[i-j]);

            for (int j = 1; i-j+1 >= 0 && i+j < n && s[i-j+1] == s[i+j]; j++) // even length palindrome
                cut[i+j+1] = min(cut[i+j+1],1+cut[i-j+1]);
        }
        return cut[n];
    }
};

```


The definition of 'cut' array is the minimum number of cuts of a sub string. More specifically, cut[n] stores the cut number of string s[0, n-1].

Here is the basic idea of the solution:

1. Initialize the 'cut' array: For a string with n characters s[0, n-1], it needs at most n-1 cut. Therefore, the 'cut' array is initialized as cut[i] = i-1

2. Use two variables in two loops to represent a palindrome:
The external loop variable 'i' represents the center of the palindrome. The internal loop variable 'j' represents the 'radius' of the palindrome. Apparently, j <= i is a must.
This palindrome can then be represented as s[i-j, i+j]. If this string is indeed a palindrome, then one possible value of cut[i+j] is cut[i-j] + 1, where cut[i-j] corresponds to s[0, i-j-1] and 1 correspond to the palindrome s[i-j, i+j];

When the loops finish, you'll get the answer at cut[s.length].

**Time Complexity** - O(n<sup>2</sup>)
**Space Complexity** - O(n)

This is most optimised approach because here it is using only O(n) extra space in this approach while in above two approach we used O(n<sup>2</sup>) extra space with same time complexity.

