solutions.content:
This problem is part 2 of the problem- [Palindrome Partitioning](https://leetcode.com/problems/palindrome-partitioning/)

**ALGORITHM**
* This solution scan the string from `left to right` (for i loop) and only checks those sub-strings centered at s[i] 
* Once a `non-palindrome string` is found, it will stop and move to `i+1`.  
* `minCUTS[i]` is used to save the minimum cuts for `s[0:i-1]`. 
* For each i, we do two for loops 
	* For j loop- to check if the substrings `s[i-j .. i+j]` (odd-length substring)  
	* `s[i-j-1.. i+j]` (even-length substring) are palindrome. 
	* By increasing j from 0, we can find all the palindrome sub-strings centered at i and update minCUTS accordingly. 
* Once we meet one non-palindrome sub-string, we stop for-j loop since we know there no further palindrome substring centered at i. 
	* This helps us avoid unnecessary palindrome substring checks, as we did in the DP algorithm. Therefore, this version is faster.

**SOLUTION**
`In C++`
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minCut(string s) {
        int len = s.size();
        vector<int> cut(len, 0);
        for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) 
        {
            cut[i] = i;
        }
        for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) 
        {
            for (int j = 0; i-j>=0 && i+j<len && s[i-j]==s[i+j]; j++)  // odd-length substrings
            {
                cut[i+j] = (i-j==0 ? 0 : min(cut[i+j], cut[i-j-1]+1));
            }
            for (int j = 0; i-j-1>=0 && i+j<len && s[i-j-1]==s[i+j]; j++)  // even-length substrings
            {
                cut[i+j] = i-j-1==0 ? 0 : min(cut[i+j], cut[i-j-2]+1);
            }
        }
        return cut[len-1];
    }
};
```
**TIME COMPLEXITY: O(N^2)**

