solutions.content:
- **Create a dp array**. This will keep the **minimum number of cuts needed from 0 to that element**.
- Initialize it with ```dp[i] = i ``` because in the worst case, we would need to cut in every space between the characters.
- Start with every character and **expand the substring around the center** as long as new characters are equal. We need to do it with odd length and even length substrings.
- While expanding:
	- Since we expand only if our expanded substring is a palindrome, we do not need a cut inside our substring. 
	- But, from our dp array definition we need to add the minimum cuts needed from the previous element that our current substring starts. We add that one too.

```
class Solution {

    public int minCut(String s) {
        if (s.isEmpty()) return 0;
        int[] minCuts = new int[s.length()];
        for (int i = 0; i < minCuts.length; i++) {
            minCuts[i] = i;
        }
        for (int i = 1; i < s.length(); i++) {
            findMin(s, minCuts, i, i);
            findMin(s, minCuts, i-1, i);
        }
        return minCuts[s.length() - 1];
    }

    private void findMin(String s, int[] minCuts, int start, int end) {
        for (; start >= 0 && end < s.length() && s.charAt(start) == s.charAt(end); start--, end++) {
            int newCut = start == 0 ? 0 : minCuts[start - 1] + 1;
            minCuts[end] = Math.min(newCut, minCuts[end]);
        }
    }
}
```

