solutions.content:
Abstract
This passage can mainly be divided into two parts - 
the first part gives a straight forward solution and 
the second part talks about how to improve its performance and get rid of the annoying "Time Limit exceeded". As far as I'm concerned, the second part's more important.

Part I
Let's define cut( k ) the action of cutting s between the kth and the (k+1)th character as the picture shows below. For instance, if s = "aabac...", cut(2) means spliting s into "aa" and "bac...", and if we continue to do cut(3), it would becomes "aa","b","ac...". 
Please note that cut(0) means a cut before s (do nothing).
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/bfcb8790-3518-4cdd-a20f-69c3b4b5a46f_1596027777.4676833.png)

Now assume we had split a string properly and use the least cuts, there should be two circumstances: 
1. we don't need to cut it cause s itself is palindrome -> cut 0 time .  
2. we need at least one cut to finish the job:
	Let cut(r) be the rightmost cut, then the right part must be a palindrome. In the picture, we have r = 5 and the right part is "ee" - a plaindrome.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ae091786-fab6-4564-a7bb-b8a4bbe80bf8_1596032896.3118505.png)


We can find that:
	**minCut(s) = minCut(left part of r) + 1**
	**=>  minCut(s) = minCut(s.substr(0,r)) + 1**
	and in the example above it becomes: 
	minCut("aabacee") = minCut("aabac") + 1;

Unfortunately, we don't know where exactly the r is, therefore, we should scan all the possible postion and get the mininum. In short, we could let k be 0,1,2,3, ..., **s.size()**, and check whether s.substr(k), namely, the part right of position k, is a palindrome, if yes, we calculate minCut(s.substr(0,k)) + 1 and compare it to the current minimun, if no, move the the next k. 
Noticed that k=0 refers to no cut, we should define minCut(s.substr(0,0)) = -1 so that the minCut(s.substr(0,0) + 1) is 0, which indicates s itself is a palindrome - circumstance 1.

Since solving minCut(s) requires the result of
minCut(s.substr(0,0)), minCut(s.substr(0,1)), minCut(s.substr(0,2)), ... ,minCut(s.substr(0,**s.size()**)) 
We have to use DP. Save the result of minCut(s.substr(0,k)) k = 0,1,2,3...**s.size()** in a vector<int> cuts and return cuts[s.size()] and it's done.
```
class Solution {
public:
	 bool isPalindrome(const string& input) {
        int leftindex = 0;
        int rightindex = input.size() - 1;
        while (leftindex < rightindex) {
            if (input[leftindex] != input[rightindex])
                return false;
            ++leftindex;
            --rightindex;
        }
        return true;
    }
    int minCut(string s) {
        if (isPalindrome(s))
            return 0;
        vector<int> cuts(s.size()+1);
        cuts[0] = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); ++i) {
            // mincuts should a BIG number
            int mincuts = s.size()+1;
            for (int j = 0; j <= i; ++j) {
                if (isPalindrome(s.substr(j, i - j + 1))) {
                    mincuts = min(mincuts, cuts[j] + 1);
                }
                if(mincuts == 1)
                    break;
            }
            cuts[i+1] = mincuts;
        }
        return cuts[s.size()];
    }
};
```
Part II
We surely devised a solution but the server would probably give us "time limit exceeded" for "reward". Look back to our algorithm, does it really own a O(n^2) complexity ?  Actually, it's O(n^3) cause every time we check
if ( isPalindrome( s.substr ( j , i - j + 1 ) ) ), we enter a loop where we wasted too much time. The next paragrah emphasizes on how to get rid of function isPalindrome() and use a matrix instead.

Delete the function and we re-define isPalindrome a matrix which elements is of bool type.
```
vector<vector<bool>> isPalindrome(s.size(),vector<bool>(s.size()));
```
isPalindrome [ i ] [ j ] represents whether s[i : j] is a palindrome. Naturally, j>= i . 
This time we need a different method of judge isPalindrome[ i ] [ j ]. Let's start from an instance:
how do we judge whether "abcdcba" is a plindrome? - A fast solution is that to check the first and last character of that string, if they're distinct, the answer goes to false, nevertheless, if they're equivalent, the answer is same to the answer of "is bcdcb a palindrome?" ,so we have:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3461ed69-7aac-4450-852a-ba4685fd8b0f_1596035499.7717228.png)

Now we need to fill in the blanks of matrix isPalindrome, as said above, j >=i, hence we only need to finish the green blanks.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5a2e0b3c-38e8-4607-a4cc-9548253b8120_1596035963.3749006.png)

Observing the equotion when s[i] == s[j], we need to use the value isPalindrome[i+1,j-1] whose block locates south-western of [i,j]'s, just the blue arrows illustrate. In a nutshell, for the orange blocks, we have to feed them value while for yellow blocks, we could use a double-loop to calculate them.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/be72f4b5-5080-498c-88b4-12043a2acef8_1596036580.354408.png)

Here's the complete matrix.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7ffd4cc7-d8cc-4029-ad09-c12f47be0740_1596036923.9783666.png)

The Follwing's my final code.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minCut(string s) {
        //create isPalindrome matrix (higher trianular matrix indeed)
        vector<vector<bool>> isPalindrome(s.size(),vector<bool>(s.size()));
        isPalindrome[s.size()-1][s.size()-1] = true;
        for (int i = 0; i < isPalindrome.size()-1; ++i) {
            //create a higher triangular matrix and assign values on the digonal
            isPalindrome[i][i] = true;
            isPalindrome[i][i + 1] = (s[i] == s[i + 1]);
        }
        for (int i = s.size()-3; i >= 0; --i) {
            for (int j = i + 2; j < isPalindrome[i].size(); ++j) {
                isPalindrome[i][j] = (s[i] == s[j]) && isPalindrome[i + 1][j - 1];
            }
        }
    vector<int> cuts(s.size()+1);
        cuts[0] = -1;
        for (int right = 0; right < s.size(); ++right) {
            // mincuts should a BIG number
            int mincuts = s.size()+1;
            for (int left = 0; left <= right; ++left) {
                if (isPalindrome[left][right]) {
                    mincuts = min(mincuts, cuts[left] + 1);
                }
                if(mincuts == 1)
                    break;
            }
            cuts[right+1] = mincuts;
        }
        return cuts[s.size()];
    }
};
```
Creating&fill in the matrix ->O(n^2)
Calculating the vector cuts ->O(n^2)
totally time complexity -> O(n^2)

